Here, we attempt to reconcile intra- and inter-specific variation as well as account for growth-dependent and growth-independent hazards. We achieve this by evaluating the following, unified hazard function, incorporating individual-, species-, and temporal effects:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:model}
\lambda_{i}(t) = \bigg(\overbrace{\gamma_{s[i]}}^{\text{Growth independent}} + \overbrace{\alpha_{s[i]} \, \textrm{e}^{-\beta_{s[i]} \, X_i(t)}}^{\text{Growth dependent}}\bigg) \times \overbrace{\delta_{t}}^{\text{Census}}.
\end{equation}
Eq. \ref{eq:model} allows for additive growth-independent and growth-dependent effects, includes a negative exponential effect of individual's growth rate, and allows for mortality to vary among censuses, via the random effect $\delta_{t}$. Further, the parameters $\alpha_s$, $\beta_s$ and $\gamma_s$ vary by species, $s$. Here we include the effects of three species traits (wood density, $\rho$, shade-intolerance, $\upsilon$, and maximum dbh, $\psi$), as well as a species random effect that captures any remaining species-level differences that is not otherwise accounted for by these traits (for details see Methods).

To validate this model, we fit a series of other commonly used parametric hazard functions and compare their skill in predicting tree mortality for \Sexpr{n_inds(BCI_model_dataset_true_dbh)} individuals from \Sexpr{n_spp(BCI_model_dataset_true_dbh)} tree species at Barro Colorado Island (BCI), Panama (Fig. \ref{fig1}). The data are repeat censuses of stem diameter and tree status (alive vs. dead) taken approximately at 5-year intervals over a 15 yr period (Fig. \ref{fig1}A). In total \Sexpr{n_obs(BCI_model_dataset_true_dbh)} observations were used to fit these models. We compare the skill of different hazard functions in predicting outcomes in novel data (i.e. not used in model fitting) via 10-fold cross-validation (Fig. \ref{fig1}D) \cite{Hooten:2015, Stone:1997tg}. Evaluating models in this way is computationally expensive, making it impossible to run all possible model formulations. We therefore fit models across seven iterative stages of model development. 

In stage 1, we ask whether mortality rates vary substantially among censuses, and thus, whether a census effect is required. We achieved this by fitting a constant that is invariant with respect to species, growth rate, or census period (i.e. a null model) and compared it to the same model with a census random effect.
In stage 2, we assess whether a function incorporating both growth-dependent and growth-independent hazards outperform functions that only account for one or the other of these. Species effects were excluded, so we are simply asking which of three functional forms for $\lambda_i(t)$ (Fig. \ref{fig1}B) best predicts the survival data. The simplest form (Fig. \ref{fig1}B, left) assumes a constant growth-independent hazard rate. The second form (Fig. \ref{fig1}B, middle) assumes the risk of dying declines towards an asymptote of zero as growth increases. The third form (eq. Fig. \ref{fig1}B, right) is the summation of the two previous models; this allows $\lambda_i(t)$ to decrease exponentially with increasing growth rate, but, unlike a standard negative exponential, asymptoting at some baseline hazard $\textgreater 0$. Combined, these three models capture a variety of functional responses previously proposed (e.g. \cite{Kobe:1995tw, Wyckoff:2000un}), including effects represented in current vegetation models \cite{Moorcroft:2001ws,McDowell:2011dr}, which have not previously been systematically compared. We also investigate which growth measure (stem diameter, stem area increment) more skilfully predicts growth-dependent mortality.
In stage 3, we examine whether including wood density (a species-level trait) improved model skill, and if so, whether the effect of wood density was on growth-dependent, growth-independent, or both hazards. Finally, we fit a model that allowed parameters to vary by species-level variation that was otherwise not captured by wood density. This allowed us to ask what proportion of inter-specific hazard variability is explained by wood density. Using the final ``best'' model we also conducted post-hoc tests, to determine how species-level parameters were associated with their maximum size and light requirement.

\section*{Results}

\subsection*{Mortality over time}
Comparing the three 5-year intervals between censuses from 1995 to 2010, we found average mortality rates progressively decreasing over time. The highest proportion of trees death occurred between 1995\textendash 2000 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_dbh, 1)}\%) followed by 2000\textendash 2005 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_dbh, 2)}\%) and 2005\textendash 2010 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_dbh, 3)}\%). Consequently, when we allowed hazard rates to be scaled by census (i.e. adding term $\delta$) we observed a small, but significant, increase in predictive skill (Fig. \ref{fig2}A). Individual census effects can be found in Table S1.

